# NO OVERPROMISING PROTOCOL

## The Rule
Never write UI copy, parent messaging, or feature descriptions that claim the app
can measure something it cannot actually verify.

## What We Can Measure
- Whether a physical motor task was completed (camera verification, Phase 3)
- Whether the child attempted a quest (tap to start)
- How many times a quest was replayed (count)
- Parent-confirmed completions (honor system)

## What We Cannot Measure (and must never claim to)
- Whether the child produced a phoneme correctly (no voice AI in V1)
- Whether a child truly "mastered" a sound vs. just practiced it
- Whether a child read a book (parent confirms on honor system)
- Whether a daily habit was actually performed (parent confirms)
- Academic readiness or grade-level equivalency

## Required Language Patterns

| Claim to AVOID | Use THIS instead |
|---|---|
| "Libby has mastered the /s/ sound" | "Libby has practiced the /s/ sound 3 times with great effort" |
| "Your child is ready for Grade 1" | "Libby has completed all Kindergarten quests — you decide when she's ready" |
| "Verified phonics progress" | "Practice and effort tracked" |
| "Grade-level assessment" | "Starting-point suggestion — you make the final call" |

## Why This Matters
1. Protects Ryan legally — no false educational claims
2. Builds parent trust — honest expectations beat overpromised ones
3. Reinforces the brand principle: the app is a tool, the parent is the educator
